data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert count explicitly — failure shows "Expected:3. Actual:X"
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all are active — CollectionAssert works on ICollection
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | `Assert.IsTrue(cond, "msg")` | Always add a message for LINQ predicates |
| `users.Single(…)` then null check | `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(…))` | `Single` throws if missing — not an assert failure |
| `CollectionAssert` | Use for contains/subset/uniqueness checks | `CollectionAssert.Contains`, `.IsSubsetOf`, `.AllItemsAreUnique` |

**Also consider [FluentAssertions](https://fluentassertions.com/)** if you want richer syntax:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```

This gives the most descriptive failure messages out of the box.
